To index through characters in a string in Rust, you can use the `chars()` method to obtain an iterator over the Unicode scalar values of the string's characters. You can then use the indexing syntax (`[]`) to access individual characters.

Here's an example:

```rust
fn main() {
    let string = "Hello, World!";

    // Iterate over individual characters
    for (index, char) in string.chars().enumerate() {
        println!("Character at index {} is: {}", index, char);
    }

    // Access specific characters
    let third_char = string.chars().nth(2);

    match third_char {
        Some(char) => println!("Character at index 2 is: {}", char),
        None => println!("String is too short or index is out of range"),
    }
}
```
In the code snippet above, the `chars()` method is called on the string to obtain an iterator over its characters. The `enumerate()` method is then used to iterate over the characters along with their corresponding index.

To access a specific character at a given index, you can use the `nth()` method on the iterator. Note that this method returns an `Option<char>` because the index may be out of range if it exceeds the length of the string. Make sure to handle the possibility of `None` being returned.

