To get the last 5 characters of a string in Rust, you can use the slice syntax. Here's an example:

```rust
fn main() {
    let string = "Hello, World!";
    let last_chars = &string[string.len() - 5..];

    println!("Last 5 characters: {}", last_chars);
}
```

In the code snippet above, `string.len()` returns the length of the string. By subtracting 5 from this length, we get the starting index for the last 5 characters. We then use the slice syntax `[starting_index..]` to get a slice of the string from the starting index to the end of the string.

The variable `last_chars` will contain the last 5 characters of the string, and it can be printed or used in further operations as needed.

